After gathering in Tahrir Square, the protest moved to [[Ministry of Interior (Egypt)|MOI]], then to [[Supreme Constitutional Court of Egypt]] and finally towards the Israeli embassy. The 2011 Israeli embassy attack occurred later Cairo Egypt when Egyptian protesters entered the Israeli Embassy after tearing down the wall surrounding the building that houses it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/09/20119993150747146.html |title=Egyptians protest against military rule - Middle East |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=2001-09-11 |accessdate=2011-09-10}}</ref> Police has fired tear gas into the crowds.<ref name="IsraeliEmbassy">{{cite news|author=From Mohamed Fadel Fahmy, For CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/09/09/egypt.protests/index.html |title=Protesters in Egypt breach wall, enter Israeli Embassy - CNN.com |publisher=Edition.cnn.com |date= 24 August 2011|accessdate=2011-09-10}}</ref> Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman Yigal Palmor said about 3,000 protesters had torn apart the wall,<ref name="IsraeliEmbassy"/> forcing the [[EgyptâIsrael relations|Israeli ambassador to Egypt]] to flee<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/egypt-on-alert-after-embassy-attack-20110911-1k3pi.html|publisher='Sydney Morning Herald'' | date=11 September 2011}}</ref> The military restored state of emergency. Egyptian activists denounce a political manipulation to restore the state of emergency.
